{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0,0,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74142"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59632"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1636"},{"type":"tags","id":"4135"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74142"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with vaginal bleeding at 12 weeks gestation. An ultrasound shows a \u0027snowstorm\u0027 appearance with no visible fetus. A suction curettage is performed and tissue is sent for histological examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological appearance of a complete hydatidiform mole?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enlarged, fluid-filled villi with circumferential trophoblastic hyperplasia","Normal-sized villi with focal trophoblastic hyperplasia","Small, fibrotic villi with scant trophoblast","Mixed population of normal and enlarged villi","Enlarged villi with prominent fetal vessels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA complete hydatidiform mole shows \u003Cstrong\u003Eenlarged, fluid-filled villi with circumferential trophoblastic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E. The villi appear swollen and grape-like due to fluid accumulation (hydropic change), and there is pronounced proliferation of both syncytiotrophoblast and cytotrophoblast around the entire circumference of the villi. Notably, fetal vessels are absent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other features described are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal-sized villi with focal trophoblastic hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is more consistent with partial moles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall, fibrotic villi with scant trophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E - This appears in non-viable pregnancies but not in molar pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed population of normal and enlarged villi\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of partial moles, not complete moles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnlarged villi with prominent fetal vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - Complete moles lack fetal vessels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese histological features are important diagnostically as they help distinguish complete moles from partial moles and other abnormal pregnancies. Complete moles have a diploid genome that is entirely paternal in origin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Complete hydatidiform moles show enlarged, fluid-filled villi with circumferential trophoblastic hyperplasia and absence of fetal vessels.","Complete hydatidiform moles have a diploid genome that is entirely paternal in origin.","The histological appearance of complete moles is diagnostic and helps distinguish them from partial moles."],"references":["Lepore A, Conran RM. Educational Case: Hydatidiform Molar Pregnancy. Acad Pathol. 2021 Jan 28;8:2374289520987256. doi: 10.1177/2374289520987256. PMID: 33598531; PMCID: PMC7863141.","Chun T, Dickman E. Molar pregnancy. West J Emerg Med. 2010 May;11(2):228. PMID: 20823989; PMCID: PMC2908674","Ghassemzadeh S, Farci F, Kang M. Hydatidiform Mole. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459155/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:33:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:35:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74142"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ